ics, critic Laurie Winer shows how he orchestrated a collective reimagining of America, urging it forward with a subtly progressive vision of the relationship between country and city, rich and poor, America and the rest of the world. His rejection of bitterness, his openness to strangers, and his optimistic humor shaped not only the musical but the American dream itself. His vision can continue to be a touchstone to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Entertainment & Performing Arts.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300269123?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300269123423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300269123/original  a978-3-11-074978-6  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY